Caroline buy things for nobody's behoof but  my 
own. I remonstrated, but she told me she was 
spending nothing. Gloves, beautiful gloves, several pairs, of different tints and colours; handkerchiefs ; cravats and neck ribbands ; collars and laces ; 
boots and shoes. Then she went into a milliner's 
and bought me a new bonnet. We were all the 
morning about it, in the course of which I saw a 
good deal of Philadelphia. Then, as soon as lunch 
was over, we set about trying on dresses, and doing 
the little that was needful to make one of them fit 
me. At dinner Mr. Birkenstall asked me how I 
felt? 

" I feel guilty," I said. " Caroline has spent the 
whole day upon me and my dress." 

" I presume she would have felt guilty if she had 
not done it," he returned. " Don't you know, Desire, that the principal business of a woman is to 
dress herself ? " 

"No," said I, bluntly. 

"Your education is not finished." 

"What is the purpose of her dressing herself, 
then?" 

" Ah," said Mr. Birkenstall smiling, " do you ask 
me that? I am curious to see how things will 
approve themselves to your judgment. Wait till 
after Mrs. Marshall's party; and then you shall tell 
me what you think is the answer to your own 
question." 

So to-morrow comes the party; and I suppose I
shall learn several things, besides that. 






Sep. 8. 

IT is over, and I will tell about it. 
Caroline dressed me in a white muslin, prettier 
than anything I ever had on in my life; it was 
ruffly and fleecy, and looped with blue knots hero 
and there, and she said I looked very nice. For 
me, I did not know myself; and when we joined 
