looked at me approvingly. 

"Will she do?" said Caroline. "The hat fits 
her, don't you think ? " 

It was a Leghorn flat, with a blue ribband. I 
would have liked a black ribband better, but my 
sister said for this afternoon it must be blue. 

" She will do," said Sandie. " I am going to be 
very curious to know all the new impressions De 
sire will have received before the evening is over." 

Caroline laughed, and we went at once to Mrs. 
Marshall's. 

There is no doubt but the new impressions of that 
day were various. First came delight and wonder. 
The favourable weather continuing, warm, spicy, 
and dry, all the world was in summer attire ; and 
it gave the scene an inexpressibly pretty character. Mrs. Marshall's grounds are ample, nicely 
laid out, perfectly well kept ; there was an abundance of pleasant shade, groves of ornamental trees, 



 

copses, clumps of shrubbery, beds of gay flowers 
and stretches of well shaven green turf. Every 
where seats were placed ; in every shady spot, in 
every nice point for seeing anything pretty ; and 
as we entered the grounds the picture they presented was an exceedingly gay and lively one. It 
looked at first sight as if the flowers had forsaken 
their sphere and taken to walking and promenad 
ing. What I would have liked now would have 
been an invisible cap, and liberty to wander about 
and look at everybody and everything ; but of 
course nothing of the kind was to be thought of. 
I could as little be free as invisible. 

My next experience was a gentleman whom Mrs. 
Marshall charged with the care of me. She told 
him I was a stranger, and confided it to him to 
shew me the grounds. So we set out. But I could 
see nothing half so well with him as without him. 
He was a middle-aged man, a little bald, with 
rather prominent light blue eyes; and I thought 
he did not exactly know what to do with me. At 
least he did not know what to say to me ; and I 
did not know what to say to him. The sense of 
this became so painful to me that I could neither 
see or enjoy in any direction, for thinking that I 
ought to talk ; when I could not talk. Mr. Stone, 
that was his name, remarked indeed once that it 
was very warm; to which of course I assented, as 
it was impossible to dispute it; and then he said 
that it was a pretty scene, which was likewise undeniable; I could only endorse his opinion. Then 



 

he asked me if I would like to look at the croquet 
