to hear the rest of his story? I said, " yes, if he 
pleased ! " 

"My two young Swiss were alike in their su 
preme devotion to the dance. So they danced 
wherever they could, whenever they met. Their 
courtship was dancing, whatever their life might 
turn out to be. But the life never came to them 
together. The girl caught cold at a merry-making, 
and died. 

"Then her lover was desolate. Dancing was 
ended, and everything else, for him; he avoided 
society and lived alone as much as he could. Neither did his sorrow give way with time, or any 
thing induce him to change his solitary manner of 
life. His love was true love, you see. A long time 
passed. One summer he was employed in cutting 
wood high up on the mountain ; and while so employed had his home in a retired little hamlet, like 
wise high up on the mountain, near the regions 
of perpetual snow and ice. This little hamlet was 
deserted as well as retired; forsaken perhaps be 
cause of its exposed situation and great severity of 
climate ; at any rate it had long had no inhabitants. 
He lived in it alone. Therefore he was greatly surprised one evening on returning late from work, to 
see that the window-shutters of a ruined old house 
opposite his hut were open, light was pouring out 
from them, and the gay notes of a violin floated 
merrily out on the air. Moreover, the music was 
dance music, festive and merry. Many a day 
was it since the fellow had heard a violin; and 



 

now lie listened, and his foot beat time involuntarily ; and at last he could not stand it any longer ; 
he must see what was going on, even if he took 
no part. Of course he would take no part. He 
tipped over the road on the ends of his toes, saw 
that the house door was not quite shut, pushed it 
open, found the inner door also manageable, and 
peeped in. The room was fully lighted, though 
he could see neither fire nor candles; the illumi 
nation seemed to come from the dancers, who 
were whirling round the room in a wild, furious 
waltz. Yet every face was pale and grave and 
earnest, as if it had been a sad rather than a mer 
ry occasion that they were celebrating. They were 
dressed in old-fashioned costumes ; but the looker-
on could hear now and then between the notes of 
the violin, a singular clicking and clashing, as of 
bits of ice together; and then, looking more narrowly, he observed that the dresses and even the 
hair of the company were hung full of little icicles, 
and their very fingers had the appearance of having been turned to water crystals. There was no 
noise but that of the music and the ice clinking ; no 
voices made themselves heard; the revelry was as 
still as it was wild." 

" Where did the music come from ? " 
" yes, the music ! Two musicians sat upon the 
stove, in which there was no fire, and played; one 
an odd little humpbacked figure, with a violin, the 
other handling a bass viol. Among all the dancers 
the young man noticed one in particular; a tall figure of a girl, whose face he could not see; she wore 
a long white robe and in her hair was a glittering 
chaplet. He could not see her face, yet something 
about the figure seemed strangely familiar ; he 
could not turn his eyes away from her. Sudden 
ly she faced him, and the young man shrank back 
with a cry of horror; it was the face of his bridn 
whom he had lost." 

" Were they married ? " 

" No, but the Germans call a lady a bride before 
her wedding, instead of after; from the time of 
her betrothal. The poor young man gave way 
and fled ; ran over the road, shut himself up in his 
hut, and covered himself up in his bed ; but as you 
may suppose, he was unable to sleep. His limbs 
shook, his horror was like a cold bath; he could 
not get out of his ears the sound of the music and 
of the clinking flakes of ice. Hours may have 
gone by; and then he was conscious of a bright 
light that was filling his own little room. He took 
his head from under the bedclothes and watched, 
full of fear, as he saw the light in a sort gather itself into form and substance and assume the out 
lines of a human shape. He guessed who it must 
be, and shuddering closed his eyes. But now he 
heard the clink of the ice flakes again, close to his 
bed; his coverlet was gently drawn back and an 
icy hand passed over his face. This was too much 
to bear; he started up and called out, In Heaven's 
name, who are you? Then he felt an icy kiss 
upon his lips. 



 

"According to the popular belief, spirits of the 
departed cannot begin a conversation with the living. But if they are spoken to, then they are per 
mitted to breathe human breath and to carry on 
a discourse with a living person, which may last 
from midnight to cockcrow. Also, the kiss of their 
lips takes away the fear naturally felt before then. 
So the way was smooth now for an interview. The 
apparition answered that she was his lost love; 
that she had come from the glacier; and that at 
this season she was obliged to come up here with 
the rest of her companions and dance. She in 
formed the young man that the sin of their life 
time formed their punishment in purgatory. How 
long I should have had to do penance, she went 
on, if you had not spoken to me! Now the salvation of us all depends upon you. Will you help 
us? 

" He answered with a solemn promise; and they 
talked together during the rest of the night. 

"Next day the young man went to see his priest. 
They had a long conference. When midnight 
came again, the two met at the church, went in, 
the priest fastened the doors on the inside; and 
what passed nobody knew, but when after a time 
they came out again, the young man's face was 
pale, but resolute and glad. From that day he 
had nothing more to do with merry-makings. He 
was a changed man. He spoke little, prayed much 
for the poor souls in the glacier, and did a great 
deal of good in the world. He remained unmarried 



 

till his death. After his death, the priest revealed 
what until then he had been obliged to keep secret. 
He told how that night in the church, after receiving the young man's confession, he had solemnly 
married him to the lady of his love. The bride 
had been invisible to the priest, but not so to the 
bridegroom, who had given his life to her to save 
her and her companions of dancing tendencies 
from the purgatory of the freezing glacier. What 
do you think of that for a story, Miss Burgoyne ? " 

I looked away, for I had been eagerly listening, 
and could not at first find an answer. 

"What do you say to such constancy? " 

" I do not think much of it. Any good and true 
man would do as much." 

"You think so?" 

"Do not you, Mr. Iredell?" 

"I am afraid it is rare. Men are selfish." 

"But true love seeks not her own. I am sure 
there are women, and men, who would give their 
lives, or the comfort and happiness of their lives, 
which is more, to secure those they love from 
great evil." 

And ask no return ? " 

No return but that fact. Why, you believe 
that, don't you?" 

" If the poor mountaineers of the German Alps 
believe it, why should not I ? " 

"Are you thinking that there is more truth 
among mountaineers than among people that live 
in low lands ? " 



 

I was not thinking that. But perhaps it is 
true." 

" 
" Why should it be true?" 

"I do not know; but there may be several reasons. The influence of grand nature scenes can 
not be without effect. And then life that is led in 
a mountainous country cannot be one of ease and 
