customs and manners act and react upon one an 
other." 

And then he went on to tell me of the first; a ba 
zui in an Eastern city. I shall never forget that
talk. It was as good as the Arabian Nights. I 
seemed to myself to be there, going through the 
streets of some Oriental wonderplace; with the 
warm colouring, the soft twilight, the hush of the 
great mart, in the midst of all its business. I saw 
the large courtyards, passed from time to time, 
where the camels were getting unloaded in the 
shade of the plane trees, and the idling Turks 
were sitting looking on. Then the little shops, all 
along the- Bazar ways; the Asiatic variety and odd 
ity and beauty of Ihe wares, which Mr. Iredell was 
so good as to describe to me; having, I suppose, a 
kindly sympathy for my womanish eagerness of 
curiosity. lie told me of embroidered cloths, mar 
vellous in pattern and execution; silk gauzes of 
rarest manufacture; inhiid weapons, and old china. 
I followed him in fancy, going on through one 
after another street or alley of the bazar; I drank 
almond milk with him nL a sort of little restaurant, 
and looked about me at the cook shops, the confectioner's ; saw the skewers full of bits of broiled mut 
ton, the honey cakes and the unleavened broad 
After that, we went in imagination to a seller of 
carpets, in the purely Turkish portion of the bazar ; 
where in a large, cool room the merchant's clerk 
gives us chairs, and delicate cups of coffee and cigarettes are brought, before we eriter upon the heavy 
business that has brought us there. And then the 
carpets! Turkey carpets, thick and soft and rich, 
of all sorts of colours, yet so mixed that the general 
tone is almost grave. Persian carpets, more brilliant and vivid. And after buying our carpets, on 
and on we went, through whole streets filled not 
only with one kind of shops, but the shops filled 
with only one or two kinds of ware. Think of a 
whole street of shops in which nothing is offered 
for sale but different kinds of fcz; and another 
with nothing to be seen but shoes; and another 
with silk scarfs and velvet jackets. 

"What a distance," said I at last, "between such 
a bazar, and one of our country stores ; where every 
thing is sold at once, from ).ork and candles to 
muslin and books ! " 

"And where there i&lt;s no one thing pleasant 
to look upon, or arranged with the smallest degree of the sense of beauty. While in an Oriental bazar almost every article is beautiful ; artistic 
in design, just and frequently exquisite in execution, and oftentimes absolutely wonderful in 
colour. Europeans cannot equal them; western 
imitations are unbearable. To go no further, the 



 

carpets and stuffs and embroideries and pottery 
forms, are studies of harmony and grace and sub 
dued splendour." 

" Is it just the difference between an old country 
and a new ? " said I, ruminating. 

" No, that will not do. European countries are 
not new. No, and it is not civilization. The fact is, 
that the children of Shem and the children of Ham 
are gifted with a luxurious sense of beauty in some 
things, such as the children of Japhet never had." 

" Are we the children of Japhet ? " 

"Yes." 

" And Europeans ? " 

" Certainly," said Mr. Iredell smiling. 

"I have never studied these things," said I. 
"But I thought Greek art and European art " 

" Right enough. The old Greeks had an high 
sense of beauty, both in nature and art. Yet it 
was rather intellectual and poetical than luxurious; it had little to do with colour. The art of 
the rest of Europe has been largely the outgrowth 
of religious feeling. Among all its painters there 
has been but one Titian. The children of Japhet 
are thinkers, in venters, originaters of progress, 
travellers; the children of Shem and Ham do not 
invent and do not make progress; they like to be 
still and enjoy. In. the levees of Indian princes 
to-day there is a daring and delicious use of colour, which not the most splendid of European 
courts can even rival." 

"I have never seen beautiful things," said I, 



 

coming back, "except the beautiful things of 
nature." 

"The models and patterns for all the rest," said 
Mr. Iredell. " If you have seen those your eye has 
been filled. And yet, between the country store 
you speak of, or a village fair, and the shows of 
an Eastern bazar, there is a wide, wide distance. 
That is like a small city; with its fountains, and 
even its mosques, and its public baths ; its most varied and most picturesque costumes, and its endless 
diverse kinds of merchandise; and beauty every 
where." 

"You have made me see it," I said. "I shall 
never forget it." 

"I have tired you, I fear? Never get an old 
traveller upon his rambles, if you do not want him 
to keep going. You see, I have forgotten myself." 

" I was going to say, I w r as afraid I had tired 
you," said I rising; " for you must have seen how 
I liked to listen." 

" Are you going ? " 

" Isn't it time ? " 

" Upon my word, I believe it must be," said he 
looking at the sky and then around him at the coloured lanterns, to which neither of us till now had 
paid much attention. In fact, we had been sitting 
with our backs to them, as I said, on a seat front 
ing the water ; from which the reflection of the sunset glow had long unheeded faded away. Now 
stars were out; and whun we rose up and turned 
about, we saw the grounds transformed into a 



 

gay, bright, witcliingly pretty wilderness of coloured lights and reflections. It was lovely; but 
I was sorry to turn from the quiet starlight in 
which we had been talking. I was sorry to go. 
It was time to go indeed. I was presently received and taken possession of by our hostess who 
informed me my sister was looking for me; and 
we came home. 



Sep. 9. 

I WAS up as early as usual the next morning, 
even earlier, eager to get dressed and sit down 
at my balcony door. I set the glass and the blind 
wide open and let the gentle morning air and sun 
light stream in. How glad I am of this glass door 
and balcony ! It is true, I see from it nothing so 
pretty as the heads of the old chestnut trees at 
home and the soft hilly outlines; but then I have 
no wish to see those just now ; I get instead a gay 
flash of all the c olours in the rainbow from the artemisias down in the garden. Pale yellow and or 
ange, lavender and rose and purple, copper brown 
